SNP ID: CYP1A2 or CYP1A2*1F or A-164C or A-163C
what it means: The C allele reduces enzyme function, resulting in slow metabolism of caffeine. This SNP also affects metabolism of certain toxins.
recommendations for (+/+): Limit caffeine intake, as it may exacerbate stress and interfere with sleep. Consider adaptogenic herbs for occasional fatigue. Include raw cruciferous vegetables in the diet to support detoxification. Limit grapefruit juice consumption, which has a mild inhibitory effect on this enzyme.
recommendations for (+/-): Limit caffeine intake, as it may exacerbate stress and interfere with sleep. Consider adaptogenic herbs for occasional fatigue.
tests: Self-reported daily caffeine intake, stress levels and sleep habits.

what it means: Reduced capacity to detoxify hydrogen peroxide, a reactive oxygen species.
recommendations for (+/+): Consume a diet rich in fruits and vegetables. Include cruciferous vegetables such as broccoli, Brussels sprouts, arugula, kale and cauliflower. Antioxidant supplements may be recommended.
recommendations for (+/-): Consume a diet rich in fruits and vegetables. Include cruciferous vegetables such as broccoli, Brussels sprouts, arugula, kale and cauliflower. Antioxidant supplements may be recommended.

what it means: Reduced ability to conjugate certain toxins with glutathione.
recommendations for (+/+): Consume a diet rich in fruits and vegetables. Include cruciferous vegetables such as broccoli, Brussels sprouts, arugula, kale and cauliflower. Supplements to support detoxification may be recommended.
recommendations for (+/-): Consume a diet rich in fruits and vegetables. Include cruciferous vegetables such as broccoli, Brussels sprouts, arugula, kale and cauliflower. Supplements to support detoxification may be recommended.

what it means: The T allele is associated with reduced enzyme activity.
recommendations for (+/+): Limit exposure to tobacco smoke. Exercise regularly and consume cruciferous vegetables.
recommendations for (+/-): Limit exposure to tobacco smoke. Exercise regularly and consume cruciferous vegetables.

what it means: Alters the distribution of the SOD2 enzyme (cytosolic vs. mitochondrial), which may compromise antioxidant defenses.
recommendations for (+/+): Studies suggest that higher consumption of foods rich in lycopene and other antioxidants support breast and prostate health in individuals with this genetic variation. Emphasize colorful fruits and vegetables, and include cruciferous vegetables such as broccoli, Brussels sprouts, arugula, kale and cauliflower.
recommendations for (+/-): Studies suggest that higher consumption of foods rich in lycopene and other antioxidants support breast and prostate health in individuals with this genetic variation. Emphasize colorful fruits and vegetables, and include cruciferous vegetables such as broccoli, Brussels sprouts, arugula, kale and cauliflower.

what it means: Associated with deficits in BDNF production. BDNF is important for maintaining mood and cognitive function.
recommendations for (+/+): Regular exercise is one of the best ways to support your bodys ability to make BDNF. Your diet should include fruits, vegetables and tea, which are rich in polyphenols, and fermented foods such as kefir or yogurt, which provide beneficial bacteria that support natural BDNF production. Include zinc-rich foods such as spinach, nuts, seeds, lean meats and omega-3 fatty acids from fish such as wild salmon, sardines and herring.
recommendations for (+/-): Regular exercise is one of the best ways to support your bodys ability to make BDNF. Your diet should include fruits, vegetables and tea, which are rich in polyphenols, and fermented foods such as kefir or yogurt, which provide beneficial bacteria that support natural BDNF production. Include zinc-rich foods such as spinach, nuts, seeds, lean meats and omega-3 fatty acids from fish such as wild salmon, sardines and herring.

what it means: Val: Lower dopamine levels due to faster degradation. Met: Higher dopamine levels due to slower degradation.
recommendations for (+/+): Consider relaxation techniques, psychotherapy, meditation and music therapy to help support your natural ability to handle stress. Ensure adequate magnesium intake, and minimize or avoid the use of stimulants.
recommendations for (+/-): Consider relaxation techniques, psychotherapy, meditation and music therapy to help support your natural ability to handle stress. Ensure adequate magnesium intake, and minimize or avoid the use of stimulants.
recommendations for (-/-): Consume adequate protein, which provides amino acid precursors of dopamine and other neurotransmitters. Exercise may also help to support daily cognitive function, alertness and mood.
tests: Self-reported stress levels, sleep satisfaction and mood.

what it means: The T allele is associated with altered dopamine signaling. This may affect short- term memory performance.
recommendations for (+/+): Consume a diet high in protein, fiber, whole grains, vegetables and fruits. Emphasize lean meats, poultry, eggs and fish as protein sources, which are rich sources of amino acid precursors of dopamine and other neurotransmitters. Your health care provider will determine whether a supplement is right for you. This SNP may alter the way you respond to antipsychotic agents.
recommendations for (+/-): Consume a diet high in protein, fiber, whole grains, vegetables and fruits. Emphasize lean meats, poultry, eggs and fish as protein sources, which are rich sources of amino acid precursors of dopamine and other neurotransmitters. Your health care provider will determine whether a supplement is right for you. This SNP may alter the way you respond to antipsychotic agents.

what it means: Reduced ability to activate folates to 5-MTHF.
recommendations for (+/+): Eat plenty of green, leafy vegetables, which provide folate in a form the body can use.
recommendations for (+/-): Eat plenty of green, leafy vegetables, which provide folate in a form the body can use.

what it means: This enzyme converts tryptophan to 5-HTP, the precursor of serotonin, which is important for emotional well- being.
recommendations for (+/+): Your diet should emphasize fruits, vegetables, fiber, and adequate protein, all of which provide essential nutrients and phytochemicals that support emotional wellness. Emphasize protein sources such as lean meats and poultry, which are rich in tryptophan, a precursor of serotonin. A supplement may be recommended if other factors indicate the need for mood support.
recommendations for (+/-): Your diet should emphasize fruits, vegetables, fiber, and adequate protein, all of which provide essential nutrients and phytochemicals that support emotional wellness. Emphasize protein sources such as lean meats and poultry, which are rich in tryptophan, a precursor of serotonin. A supplement may be recommended if other factors indicate the need for mood support.

what it means: Individuals with GG genotypes are more susceptible to the vascular effects of high saturated fat intake (45% of total calories).
recommendations for (+/+): Limit total fat intake to 30% of total daily calories. Consume saturated fats sparingly. Limit sodium intake to 2,300 mg per day.
recommendations for (+/-): Limit total fat intake to 30% of total daily calories. Consume saturated fats sparingly. Limit sodium intake to 2,300 mg per day.

what it means: This polymorphism alters plasma AGT levels, with a 10_30% increase among C allele carriers. These individuals may be more sensitive to the effects of dietary sodium on vascular function.
recommendations for (+/+): Limit sodium intake to 2,300 mg per day and maintain adequate intake of potassium-rich foods, such as fruits and vegetables. Aim for a daily potassium intake of 4,700 mg per day.
recommendations for (+/-): Limit sodium intake to 2,300 mg per day and maintain adequate intake of potassium-rich foods, such as fruits and vegetables. Aim for a daily potassium intake of 4,700 mg per day.

what it means: Individuals with the C allele (particularly CC genotypes) are predisposed to higher levels of C-reactive protein (CRP).
recommendations for (+/+): Manage stress, maintain a healthy weight, get adequate sleep and exercise regularly.
recommendations for (+/-): Manage stress, maintain a healthy weight, get adequate sleep and exercise regularly.

what it means: C allele carriers metabolize caffeine more slowly and are at greater risk for adverse cardiovascular health effects of moderate to heavy caffeinated coffee consumption (at least 2-3 cups of coffee per day).
recommendations for (+/+): Be mindful of caffeine intake. Limit caffeinated coffee consumption to a maximum of 2 cups per day. Consider alternatives, such as adaptogenic herbs, for occasional fatigue.
recommendations for (+/-): Be mindful of caffeine intake. Limit caffeinated coffee consumption to a maximum of 2 cups per day. Consider alternatives, such as adaptogenic herbs, for occasional fatigue.

what it means: The TT genotype enhances the benefits of regular aerobic exercise on vascular function, while G allele carriers are more likely to exhibit a typical or modest response.
recommendations for (+/+): If maintaining healthy vascular function is a clinical goal, regular aerobic exercise should be a top priority.
recommendations for (+/-): If maintaining healthy vascular function is a clinical goal, regular aerobic exercise should be a top priority.

what it means: The TT genotype predicts superior response to riboflavin supplementation (1.6 mg/day), which supports vascular relaxation in these individuals. Patients with CT and CC genotypes are less likely to experience this unique benefit.
recommendations for (+/+): Maintain adequate riboflavin (vitamin B2) intake. Good sources of riboflavin include lean meats, eggs and dairy products. Supplementation is recommended if you do not tolerate these foods.
recommendations for (+/-): Maintain adequate riboflavin (vitamin B2) intake. Good sources of riboflavin include lean meats, eggs and dairy products. Supplementation is recommended if you do not tolerate these foods.

what it means: Paraoxonase-1 (PON1) is an antioxidant enzyme that helps to maintain lipoprotein redox status and cardiovascular health. This polymorphism, known as Q192R, alters its antioxidant activity.
recommendations for (+/+): Consume a polyphenol-rich diet. Major sources of polyphenols that support PON1 include berries, pomegranate juice, tea, red wine. Mediterranean diet constituents, such as nuts, fruits and vegetables, have been effective in supporting this enzyme. Maintain adequate intake of antioxidants (vitamins C, E, beta carotene), selenium and essential fatty acids.
recommendations for (+/-): Consume a polyphenol-rich diet. Major sources of polyphenols that support PON1 include berries, pomegranate juice, tea, red wine. Mediterranean diet constituents, such as nuts, fruits and vegetables, have been effective in supporting this enzyme. Maintain adequate intake of antioxidants (vitamins C, E, beta carotene), selenium and essential fatty acids.

what it means: In the HERITAGE multicenter clinical study, greater increases in HDL were achieved among CT and CC genotypes following an exercise program. Carriers of the TT variant had a typical response.
recommendations for (+/+): If improving HDL cholesterol is a core objective, make exercise a regular habit, as it is likely to result in significant improvements.
recommendations for (+/-): If improving HDL cholesterol is a core objective, make exercise a regular habit, as it is likely to result in significant improvements.
recommendations for (-/-): You are likely to achieve typical improvements in HDL cholesterol with regular exercise.
tests: HDL-C: Men: 40 mg/dL or below; Women: 50 mg/dL or below

what it means: The C allele may increase the risk of coenzyme Q10 depletion in individuals receiving statins.
recommendations for (+/+): Consider coenzyme Q10 supplementation if receiving statins.
recommendations for (+/-): Consider coenzyme Q10 supplementation if receiving statins.
tests: For patients receiving statins: Serum coenzyme Q10: 0.37_2.20 _g/mL

what it means: The A allele is associated with increased alpha- adrenergic receptor expression, which may affect insulin release by the pancreas.
recommendations for (+/+): Consider relaxation techniques, meditation or related stress management strategies.
recommendations for (+/-): Consider relaxation techniques, meditation or related stress management strategies.
tests: Fasting glucose: Adults: 70 - 100 mg/dL, HbA1c: Adults: 4.0 _ 5.6%, Serum cortisol: AM: 7 _ 25 mcg/dL, PM: 2 _ 14 mcg/dL

what it means: The T allele may influence glucose homeostasis.
recommendations for (+/+): Follow a Mediterranean diet or similar, reduce carbohydrate intake, eliminate sugars, and exercise regularly.
recommendations for (+/-): Follow a Mediterranean diet or similar, reduce carbohydrate intake, eliminate sugars, and exercise regularly.
tests: Fasting glucose: Adults: 70 - 100 mg/dL, HbA1c: Adults: 4.0 _ 5.6%

what it means: The A allele may influence glucose homeostasis. Zinc has been shown to modify this effect.
recommendations for (+/+): Ensure adequate zinc intake.
recommendations for (+/-): Ensure adequate zinc intake.
tests: Alkaline phosphatase (a marker of zinc status): Men: 45 _ 115 U/L, Women: 37 _ 144 U/L, Fasting glucose: Adults: 70 - 100 mg/dL, HbA1c: Adults: 4.0 _ 5.6%

what it means: Associated with low blood levels of adiponectin, a hormone that maintains healthy glucose and lipid metabolism. This relationship has been demonstrated in Caucasians of European descent. Its relevance to other ethnic groups has not been established.
recommendations for (+/+): Omega-3 fatty acids, Alpha lipoic acid,berberine and resveratrol to support glucose homeostasis*, exercise, Mediterranean or plant-based diet emphasizing whole foods, vegetables and healthy fats
recommendations for (+/-): Omega-3 fatty acids, Alpha lipoic acid, berberine and resveratrol to support glucose homeostasis*, exercise, Mediterranean or plant-based diet emphasizing whole foods, vegetables and healthy fats
tests: Serum adiponectin is a useful method to determine a patientês levels and to monitor the effect of diet and lifestyle interventions on metabolic health. Metabolic Xtra should be considered if other testing determines that glucose homeostasis is a clinical objective.

what it means: Genetic predisposition to a higher body weight and body fat percentage. This is due, in part, to increased appetite and diminished satiety after meals. Carriers may be more likely to lose weight through diet and lifestyle modifications than non-carriers.
recommendations for (+/+): Increase protein intake, Fucoxanthin and green tea, Whole food diet emphasizing colorful fruits and vegetables, The Mediterranean diet may reduce the impact of the FTO SNP on metabolic health, Adequate sleep to help reduce cravings, Regular exercise
recommendations for (+/-): Increase protein intake, Fucoxanthin and green tea, Whole food diet emphasizing colorful fruits and vegetables, The Mediterranean diet may reduce the impact of the FTO SNP on metabolic health, Adequate sleep to help reduce cravings, Regular exercise
tests: Anthropometric measurements (body weight and body composition). Assess vitamin D levels. Correcting a deficiency may reduce the effect of the SNP on body weight.

what it means: Diminished capacity to convert omega-3 fatty acid precursors from plant sources (linolenic acid from flaxseed oil, for example) to active omega-3 fatty acids (EPA and DHA).
recommendations for (+/+): EPA and DHA
recommendations for (+/-): EPA and DHA
tests: Omega-3 index or similar blood testing is useful for monitoring. The Essential and Metabolic Fatty Acids Analysis RBC (Genova) is recommended.

what it means: Associated with increased food intake and weight gain, particularly when saturated fat intake is high.
recommendations for (+/+): Reduce saturated fat intake. In one study, consuming less than 22g/day reduced the effect of this genotype on body weight.
recommendations for (+/-): Reduce saturated fat intake. In one study, consuming less than 22g/day reduced the effect of this genotype on body weight.
tests: Anthropometric measurements (body weight and body composition).

what it means: The G allele is associated with increased production of IL-6 and higher plasma levels.
recommendations for (+/+): Manage stress, get adequate sleep and exercise regularly.
recommendations for (+/-): Manage stress, get adequate sleep and exercise regularly.

what it means: The A allele is associated with increased TNF-_ expression and higher circulating levels.
recommendations for (+/+): Manage stress, get adequate sleep and exercise regularly. Intermittent fasting and fasting mimicking diets have been shown to moderate TNF-alpha. Consider these diets only under medical supervision.
recommendations for (+/-): Manage stress, get adequate sleep and exercise regularly. Intermittent fasting and fasting mimicking diets have been shown to moderate TNF-alpha. Consider these diets only under medical supervision.

what it means: Associated with lower circulating vitamin C levels.
recommendations for (+/+): Ensure adequate intake of vitamin C. Dietary sources include citrus fruits and berries. 90 mg/day for adult men and 75 mg/day for adult women is generally adequate to maintain healthy immune function. Your healthcare practitioner will determine whether you need a supplement.
recommendations for (+/-): Ensure adequate intake o fvitamin C.Dietary sources include citrus fruits and berries. 90 mg/day for adult men and 75 mg/day for adult women is generally adequate to maintain healthy immune function. Four to five servings of fruit and vegetables typically provides approximately 200 mg. Higher doses are not necessary on the basis of this SNP alone. Your healthcare practitioner will determine whether you need a supplement.

what it means: Associated with reduced activity of diamine oxidase (DAO), an enzyme that breaks down dietary histamine.
recommendations for (+/+): Use additional assessment to confirm the need for a low-histamine diet and/or supplements. Low-histamine diets limit the intake of meats, fermented and canned foods, poultry, fish, tomatoes, chocolate, tomatoes, spinach, eggplant, avocado, and nuts. Ensure adequate intake of micronutrients needed for healthy histamine metabolism, including vitamin B6, B12, vitamin C and zinc.
recommendations for (+/-): Use additional assessment to confirm the need for a low-histamine diet and/or supplements. Low-histamine diets limit the intake of meats, fermented and canned foods, poultry, fish, tomatoes, chocolate, tomatoes, spinach, eggplant, avocado, and nuts. Ensure adequate intake of micronutrients needed for healthy histamine metabolism, including vitamin B6, B12, vitamin C and zinc.
tests: Serum DAO, Zonulin level (serum) or lactulose/mannitol (urine),  Symptoms following consumption of histamine-rich foods

what it means: Associated with altered intestinal microbiota composition.
recommendations for (+/+): Include soluble fiber, yogurt, kefir and/or fermented foods in your diet. If you are sensitive to these foods, your healthcare provider may recommend supplements.
recommendations for (+/-): Include soluble fiber, yogurt, kefir and/or fermented foods in your diet. If you are sensitive to these foods, your healthcare provider may recommend supplements.

what it means: Genetic predisposition to lactose intolerance.
recommendations for (+/+): If you are lactose intolerant, eliminate dairy foods or opt for lactose-free options. Make sure that you obtain adequate calcium from other sources.
recommendations for (+/-): If you are lactose intolerant, eliminate dairy foods or opt for lactose-free options. Make sure that you obtain adequate calcium from other sources.
tests: If acute G.I. symptoms following consumption of milk and other dairy foods, rule out dairy allergy

what it means: Enhanced colon health benefits with low processed meat intake.
recommendations for (+/+): To help maintain colon health, focus on reducing intake of processed meats, which include deli meats, sausage, ham and cured bacon. Ensure adequate dietary fiber and vegetable intake.
recommendations for (+/-): To help maintain colon health, focus on reducing intake of processed meats, which include deli meats, sausage, ham and cured bacon. Ensure adequate dietary fiber and vegetable intake.

what it means: Associated with altered microbial composition in the stomach.
recommendations for (+/+): Microbial stool test, urea breath test, PCR testing (stool)
recommendations for (+/-): Microbial stool test, urea breath test, PCR testing (stool)

what it means: Individuals with the C allele have a genetic advantage in strength and power-oriented sports that require sprinting or short, intense bursts of activity. The endurance- oriented TT genotype is linked to greater muscle soreness following these types of activities.
recommendations for (+/+): You are likely to perform best in endurance-oriented sports. If you choose to engage in strength/power sports, you may need to train more consistently to achieve a high level of performance. Since you are more likely to experience muscle soreness and/or higher cortisol following intense exercise, it is important to ensure adequate rest and recovery between workouts. Managing daily stress and getting adequate sleep will help to maintain healthy cortisol levels.
recommendations for (+/-): No recommendations
recommendations for (-/-): You are likely to perform best in strength, power and sprint-type sports. If you choose to participate in endurance events, you may need to train more consistently to achieve a high level of performance.

what it means: The G allele provides a modest genetic advantage in sports requiring fast-twitch fibers, such as sprinting and weight lifting. Individuals with the A allele are more likely to excel in endurance- oriented sports.
recommendations for (+/+): You are likely to perform best in strength, power and sprint-type sports. If you choose to engage in endurance activities, you may need to train more consistently to achieve a high level of performance.
recommendations for (+/-): No recommendations
recommendations for (-/-): You are likely to perform best in endurance-oriented sports. If you choose to engage in strength/power sports, you may need to train more consistently to achieve a high level of performance.

what it means: The CC genotype has a protective effect on tendon and ligament resilience, while the T allele is associated with increased incidence of exercise-related tendon or ligament injury.
recommendations for (+/+): Warm up properly prior to exercise, particularly before plyometrics and uphill running. Include flexibility and mobility exercises for the calves and knees as part of your routine. Use proper technique to minimize unnecessary strain on your tendons and ligaments.
recommendations for (+/-): Warm up properly prior to exercise, particularly before plyometrics and uphill running. Include flexibility and mobility exercises for the calves and knees as part of your routine. Use proper technique to minimize unnecessary strain on your tendons and ligaments.

what it means: The TT genotype reduces risk of sports related tendon and ligament injuries, according to a meta- analysis of six case control studies involving 2,314 Caucasian subjects.
recommendations for (+/+): Warm up properly prior to exercise, particularly before plyometrics and uphill running. Include flexibility and mobility exercises for the calves and knees as part of your routine. Use proper technique to minimize unnecessary strain on your tendons and ligaments.
recommendations for (+/-): Warm up properly prior to exercise, particularly before plyometrics and uphill running. Include flexibility and mobility exercises for the calves and knees as part of your routine. Use proper technique to minimize unnecessary strain on your tendons and ligaments.

what it means: The G allele has been shown to influence the resilience of the Achilles tendon.
recommendations for (+/+): Be careful with plyometrics, uphill running, or overextension of the Achilles tendon. Stretch your calf muscles and warm up and cool down properly before and after exercise sessions.
recommendations for (+/-): No recommendations

what it means: Individuals with the A allele (particularly the AA genotype) tend to experience greater increases in VO2 max with endurance training compared to those with the GG variant. In a study of 316 marathon runners, the A allele was associated with the fastest finishing times.
recommendations for (+/+): You are likely to respond well to endurance training, achieving above-average VO2 max improvements.
recommendations for (+/-): You are likely to respond well to endurance training, achieving above-average VO2 max improvements.

what it means: The TT genotype is associated with suppressed VO2 max improvements following 20 weeks of aerobic training (3 x 50 min/week at 55_75% maximal heart rate).
recommendations for (+/+): Reduced VO2 max response to endurance training. You may need to train more diligently to achieve a high level of endurance performance.
recommendations for (+/-): No recommendations

what it means: Exercise typically improves insulin sensitivity, but individual results vary. CC and CT genotypes are likely to experience greater improvements in insulin sensitivity compared to TT carriers.
recommendations for (+/+): If maintaining healthy glucose homeostasis is a clinical goal, regular exercise is likely to result in significant improvements.
recommendations for (+/-): If maintaining healthy glucose homeostasis is a clinical goal, regular exercise is likely to result in significant improvements.
recommendations for (-/-): You are likely to achieve modest improvements in insulin sensitivity with exercise. If maintaining healthy glucose homeostasis is a clinical goal, consider additional strategies to support glucose homeostasis. Your healthcare practitioner may recommend a supplement.

what it means: Individuals with the GG or GC variant are likely to experience greater fat loss with endurance training compared to those with the CC variant.
recommendations for (+/+): You are likely to experience greater fat loss with endurance training based on this genetic marker. If fat loss is an existing goal, consider endurance training as a focus.
recommendations for (+/-): You are likely to experience greater fat loss with endurance training based on this genetic marker. If fat loss is an existing goal, consider endurance training as a focus.
recommendations for (-/-): You are likely to achieve typical fat loss with endurance training.

what it means: The G allele is associated with higher VO2 max, a determinant of endurance capacity.
recommendations for (+/+): Your genotype is associated with higher endurance capacity and may experience above-average performance gains with endurance training.
recommendations for (+/-): You are likely to achieve typical or modest improvements in VO2 max through regular aerobic training. Although you lack the genetic advantage associated with the GG genotype, it is unlikely to negatively affect your fitness gains unless you compete at a high level.
recommendations for (-/-): You are likely to achieve typical or modest improvements in VO2 max through regular aerobic training. Although you lack the genetic advantage associated with the GG genotype, it is unlikely to negatively affect your fitness gains unless you compete at a high level.
